Horse Racing Analysis

Author

MC

Published

This is a quick attempt to (re-)analyse the horse-racing data from Badaya, Hartsuiker, Corley. Prompted by the fact that Espeâs original analysis (see github.com/erbadaya/horse-race-task) produced a graph that looked like an interaction, but the analysis suggested that there were only main (or simple?) effects.

Setup, Data Wrangling

All parts of this analysis are loosely based on Espeâs code. Here we load some relevant libraries, read in the experimental data, and get it broadly into shape.

Code 
library(tidyverse)
#library(lme4)
library(buildmer)
library(here)

rawData <- here("data/horse_race_exp1_rawdata.csv")
df <- read_csv(rawData) |> select(-`...1`)


# function to ensure we have up-to-date bets for all horses




df_cond <- df |>
  filter (overbet=="no") |>
  select(ppt,horse,delivery,speaker) |>
  mutate(horseN=rep(c("horse0","horse1","horse2","horse3"),max(ppt)))
  
df_money <- df |> select(ppt,starts_with("horse")) |>
  group_by(ppt) |>
  filter(row_number()==1) |> select(-horse) |>
  pivot_longer(cols=starts_with("horse"),names_to="horseN",values_to="BET")

df_ready <- left_join(df_cond,df_money)

OK, so (see code above) df_ready is now a simple dataframe with the betting data.

We have to parse the questionnaire data, at least to take out people with dodgy audio(?) and also those highly familiar with horse-racing. At the moment Iâm not going to attempt a full analysis of the questionnaire data. So to match Espeâs criteria, we need to identify the questionnaire responses with ânaturalnessâ in them, and extract scores for 3 values I think: naturalness_native, naturalness_nonnative, and P1_Q5 which is apparently betting expertise.

Code 
rPatterns <- c(
  '.*P1_Q5":',
  gambling='\\d+',
  '.*naturalness_native":',
  natnat='\\d+',
  '.*naturalness_nonnative":',
  natnon='\\d+',
  '.*'
)

df_q <- df |> filter(str_detect(response,"country_native")) |>
  select(ppt,response) |>
  separate_wider_regex(response,patterns=rPatterns)
  
df_q <- df_q |> mutate(
  outAudio=ifelse(natnat<4 | natnon <4,"OUT","in"),
  outBetting=ifelse(gambling > 3, "OUT", "in")) |>
  select(-c(gambling,natnat,natnon))

Now we need to take out the 9 participants identified by Espe from comments:

Code 
df_q <- df_q |> mutate(
  outVarious=case_when(
    ppt == 12 ~ "OUT", 
    ppt == 23 ~ "OUT",
    ppt == 40 ~ "OUT", 
    ppt == 46 ~ "OUT", 
    ppt == 279 ~ "OUT", 
    ppt == 334 ~ "OUT", 
    ppt == 505 ~ "OUT", 
    ppt == 586 ~ "OUT", 
    ppt == 617 ~ "OUT",  
    TRUE  ~ "in"
  )
)

269 participants were excluded from the analysis because they detected that the audio had been manipulated. A further 4 were removed due to expertise in horse racing.

Finally, 9 additional participants were removed because their feedback suggested that they had responded strategically during the study.

Last bit of data-munging: Remove participants from the âmasterâ dataframe, and set contrasts for the experimental conditions.

Code 
df_ready <- left_join(df_ready,df_q)
df_ready <- df_ready |> filter(outAudio=='in' &
                               outBetting=='in' &
                               outVarious=='in') |>
  select(-starts_with("out"))

df_ready <- df_ready |> mutate(delivery=factor(delivery,levels=c('fluent','disfluent')),
       speaker=factor(speaker)) # native comes before non
contrasts(df_ready$delivery) <- c(-.5,5)
contrasts(df_ready$speaker) <- c(-.5,5)

Finally, make one more column which is a ânormalised betâ column (we act as if everyone had bet out of 100).

In doing this, I noticed that (at least) one participant had bet zero on all horses, so letâs remove them.

Code 
df_ready <- df_ready |> group_by(ppt) |>
  mutate(sum=sum(BET)) |> ungroup()

p_gone=sum(df_ready$sum==0)/4

df_ready <- df_ready |> filter(sum>0) |>
  select(-sum) |>
  group_by(ppt) |> mutate(BET100=BET*100/sum(BET))

2 remaining participants bet no money on any horse, and were removed from the analysis.

Results!

So Iâm as sure as I can be that these data are the same (or at least created to the same standards) as Espeâs. Now draw a graph. NB., we have two options here: Either we scale up all of the bets so that theyâre âout of 100â or we leave as-is. As-is is on the left, scaled bet is on the right.

Code 
df_plot <- df_ready |> group_by(delivery,speaker) |> summarise(mb=mean_se(BET),mb100=mean_se(BET100))

df_plot |> ggplot(aes(x=delivery,y=mb$y,fill=speaker)) +
  geom_bar(position="dodge",stat="identity") +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mb$ymin,ymax=mb$ymax),width=.4,position=position_dodge(.9))
df_plot |> ggplot(aes(x=delivery,y=mb100$y,fill=speaker)) +
  geom_bar(position="dodge",stat="identity") +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mb100$ymin,ymax=mb100$ymax),width=.4,position=position_dodge(.9))

Perhaps violin plots might make the distributions a bit clearer:

Code 
df_ready |> ggplot(aes(x=delivery,y=BET,fill=speaker)) +
  geom_violin(alpha=.5) +
  geom_boxplot(width=.2,position=position_dodge(.9)) 
df_ready |> ggplot(aes(x=delivery,y=BET100,fill=speaker)) +
    geom_violin(alpha=.5) +
    geom_boxplot(width=.2,position=position_dodge(.9))

Analysis

Letâs fit the maximal possible model to the data:

Code 
modB <- buildmer(
  BET ~ delivery * speaker +
    (delivery * speaker | ppt) +
    (delivery * speaker | horse),
  buildmerControl=buildmerControl(direction='order',
    args=list(control=lme4::lmerControl(optimizer='bobyqa'))),
  data = df_ready
)

OK, so the maximal converging model is BET ~ 1 + delivery + speaker + delivery:speaker + (1 | horse). Coefficents are shown below.

Code

Now letâs repeat the analysis, using the DV in which all bets are scaled to a total of 100.

Code 
modB1 <- buildmer(
  BET100 ~ delivery * speaker +
    (delivery * speaker | ppt) +
    (delivery * speaker | horse),
  buildmerControl=buildmerControl(direction='order',
    args=list(control=lme4::lmerControl(optimizer='bobyqa'))),
  data = df_ready
)

The maximal converging model is BET100 ~ 1 + delivery + speaker + delivery:speaker + (1 + delivery | horse). Coefficients:

Thatâs as far as I got, but it seems to confirm Espeâs original findings. Perhaps the violin plots above give some clues as to why there is no interaction?
